ğŸ³ Perform the Docker Practical
ğŸ”¹ Step 1: Install Docker

Open your terminal and run:

sudo apt update
sudo apt install docker.io -y

ğŸ‘‰ This installs Docker from Ubuntuâ€™s official repository.
ğŸ”¹ Step 2: Check Docker Version

docker --version

âœ… You should see output like: Docker version 24.x.x, build abcdefg
ğŸ”¹ Step 3: Check Docker Service Status

sudo systemctl status docker

ğŸ“Œ If it's not active, you'll start it in the next step.
ğŸ”¹ Step 4: Start Docker Service

sudo systemctl start docker

To make Docker start automatically on boot, also run:

sudo systemctl enable docker

ğŸ”¹ Step 5: Run a Test Container

sudo docker run hello-world

âœ… You should see a message starting with â€œHello from Docker!â€
ğŸ”¹ Step 6: List All Containers (including exited)

sudo docker ps -a

This shows all containers. You'll see hello-world listed with "Exited".
ğŸ”¹ Step 7: Remove a Container

First, copy the Container ID or Name from the output of docker ps -a. For example:

sudo docker rm f67b9eef5165

Or by name:

sudo docker rm elastic_bassi

ğŸ“Œ Tip: To remove all exited containers at once:

sudo docker container prune

It will ask for confirmation (y/n).
ğŸ”¹ Step 8: Stop Docker Service

sudo systemctl stop docker

ğŸ“Œ Optional: Saves system resources when you're done.

